body:
## Problem
CorrelationMatrix computes all pairwise correlations without memoization. With 50 tickers, that's 2500 correlations. Each correlation computation is O(n) on 252 trading days. With shallow re-renders, performance degrades significantly.

## Evidence
CorrelationMatrix.tsx:49-61
```typescript
const { matrix, avg, resolvedTickers } = useMemo(() => {
  const series: Record<string, number[]> = {}
  tickers.forEach((t, i) => {
    const bars = historical[i]?.data
    if (bars) {
      series[t] = bars
        .map((b) => b.close)
        .filter((v): v is number => v != null && Number.isFinite(v))
    }
  })
  const { tickers: rt, matrix: m } = correlationMatrix(series)
  return { matrix: m, avg: avgOffDiagonal(m), resolvedTickers: rt }
}, [tickers, historical])
```
The useMemo depends on entire `historical` array, causing re-compute on any single historical update. No caching of correlation values.

## Expected
For 100+ position portfolios, correlation matrix should not re-compute on every price tick. Memoize pairwise correlations keyed by (ticker_a, ticker_b, date_range). Cache historical data separately.

## Proposed fix
1. Add caching layer: `useCorrelationCache(ticker1, ticker2) -> correlation`
2. Split useMemo: separate historical loading from correlation compute
3. Lazy-render correlation matrix: only compute visible rows (intersection observer)
4. Add `skipLargeCorrelation` flag: skip rendering if > 30 tickers
5. Benchmark: measure render time with 100 tickers

## Impact
Low-medium—UX degrades for portfolios >30 tickers, but not broken. Mostly affects performance-conscious power users.
